  "executive_summary": "Decompose the courier platform monolith into six bounded services aligned to domain boundaries: Order, Courier, Location Tracking, Notification, Payment, and Customer Account. The decomposition prioritizes deployment independence (the stated goal), respects the high-throughput nature of location tracking, and preserves strict consistency for payments. Given the team size (8 engineers), I recommend a phased strangler-fig migration rather than a big-bang rewrite, starting with the two services that have the most divergent non-functional requirements: Location Tracking (high write throughput) and Payment (strict consistency).",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Order Service",
        "responsibility": "Order lifecycle management: placement, status transitions, cancellation. Owns the order aggregate including line items and delivery metadata.",
        "boundaries": "Owns orders table/collection. Publishes domain events (OrderPlaced, OrderCancelled, OrderDelivered). Does NOT own courier assignment logic or payment execution."
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Service",
        "responsibility": "Courier profiles, availability management, assignment algorithm, and route optimization. Matches couriers to orders based on proximity, capacity, and routing efficiency.",
        "boundaries": "Owns courier profiles, availability state, and assignment records. Consumes location data from Location Tracking via events or query API. Does NOT own the raw GPS stream."
      },
      {
        "name": "Location Tracking Service",
        "responsibility": "Ingest, store, and serve real-time courier GPS positions. Handles 5,000 writes/sec peak. Provides current-position queries and geofence triggers (e.g., courier near dropoff).",
        "boundaries": "Owns all raw location data. Append-only time-series store. Publishes CourierPositionUpdated and GeofenceTriggered events. Has no knowledge of orders or payments."
      },
      {
        "name": "Notification Service",
        "responsibility": "Fan-out of customer-facing notifications across email, SMS, and push channels. Template management and delivery tracking.",
        "boundaries": "Owns notification templates and delivery logs. Consumes domain events from other services. Has no business logic — pure reaction to events. Channel providers are pluggable adapters."
      },
      {
        "name": "Payment Service",
        "responsibility": "Charge authorization, capture, and refund processing. Enforces strict transactional consistency. Integrates with payment gateway(s).",
        "boundaries": "Owns payment records, transaction ledger, and refund state. Exposes synchronous API for charge/refund operations. Does NOT initiate — always called by Order Service. Idempotency keys mandatory on all mutations."
      },
      {
        "name": "Customer Account Service",
        "responsibility": "Customer registration, authentication, profile management, saved addresses, and saved payment methods (tokenized references).",
        "boundaries": "Owns customer identity and profile data. Provides auth tokens consumed by API gateway. Saved payment method tokens are opaque references — actual card data lives in the payment gateway."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Payment Service",
        "contract": "Synchronous REST/gRPC: POST /charges {orderId, amount, currency, idempotencyKey} → {chargeId, status}. POST /refunds {chargeId, amount, idempotencyKey} → {refundId, status}.",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous — acceptable because order placement requires payment confirmation before proceeding"
      },
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Courier Service",
        "contract": "Async event: OrderPlaced → Courier Service consumes and runs assignment. Courier Service publishes CourierAssigned {orderId, courierId, estimatedPickup}.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous event-driven — order does not block on assignment"
      },
      {
        "from": "Location Tracking Service",
        "to": "Courier Service",
        "contract": "Async events: CourierPositionUpdated {courierId, lat, lng, timestamp}. Also exposes query API: GET /couriers/{id}/position → {lat, lng, timestamp} for on-demand reads.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous events for streaming; synchronous query for point reads"
      },
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Notification Service",
        "contract": "Async events: OrderPlaced, OrderStatusChanged, OrderDelivered → Notification Service reacts by sending appropriate customer notifications.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous fire-and-forget — notification failure does not block order flow"
      },
      {
        "from": "Courier Service",
        "to": "Notification Service",
        "contract": "Async events: CourierAssigned, CourierNearDropoff → triggers push notification to customer.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous"
      },
      {
        "from": "Customer Account Service",
        "to": "Order Service",
        "contract": "Order Service validates auth tokens issued by Customer Account. Order Service stores customerId as a foreign reference — no direct runtime calls needed for order flow.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — token-based identity; no runtime coupling beyond auth"
      },
      {
        "from": "Location Tracking Service",
        "to": "Notification Service",
        "contract": "Async event: GeofenceTriggered {courierId, orderId, fenceType} → Notification sends 'courier is arriving' push.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1. Customer authenticates via Customer Account Service, receives JWT. 2. Customer places order → Order Service validates, calls Payment Service synchronously to authorize charge. 3. Order Service publishes OrderPlaced event. 4. Courier Service consumes OrderPlaced, queries Location Tracking for nearby couriers, runs assignment algorithm, publishes CourierAssigned. 5. Courier app sends GPS updates every 10s → Location Tracking Service ingests at high throughput. 6. Location Tracking publishes position events; Courier Service uses these for ETA recalculation. 7. Location Tracking detects geofence proximity, publishes GeofenceTriggered. 8. Notification Service consumes all relevant events and fans out to appropriate channels. 9. On delivery confirmation, Order Service captures payment via Payment Service and publishes OrderDelivered.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Strangler Fig Migration",
        "rationale": "Team has 3 years in a monolith with moderate operational maturity. A big-bang rewrite is too risky. Extract services incrementally: Location Tracking first (most divergent NFRs, easiest to isolate), then Payment (strict consistency boundary), then remaining services."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Event-Driven Architecture (Async Messaging)",
        "rationale": "Achieves the primary goal of deployment decoupling. Services communicate via domain events through a message broker. Only the Order→Payment interaction is synchronous, because payment authorization is a blocking precondition."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Database-per-Service",
        "rationale": "Each service owns its data store. Location Tracking uses a time-series DB (e.g., TimescaleDB or InfluxDB) optimized for 5K writes/sec. Payment uses a relational DB with ACID transactions. Other services use Postgres. No shared databases."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "API Gateway",
        "rationale": "Single entry point for client apps. Handles auth token validation, rate limiting, and request routing. Prevents clients from needing to know individual service addresses."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Idempotent Operations",
        "rationale": "Payment Service requires idempotency keys on all write operations to handle retries safely. This is critical for financial correctness in a distributed system."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Choreography over Orchestration",
        "rationale": "For the 8-engineer team, choreography via events is simpler to operate than a central orchestrator. Each service reacts to events it cares about. Avoids a single coordination bottleneck. Traceability addressed via correlation IDs."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Order Management",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Order (root: orderId; entities: OrderLineItem, DeliveryDetails; values: Money, Address)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Operations",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Courier (root: courierId; entities: CourierProfile, Availability; values: VehicleType, ServiceZone)", "Assignment (root: assignmentId; values: EstimatedPickupTime, Route)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Location Tracking",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["CourierPosition (root: courierId+timestamp; values: GeoPoint, Accuracy, Speed)", "Geofence (root: fenceId; values: GeoPolygon, TriggerRadius)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Payments",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["PaymentTransaction (root: transactionId; entities: Charge, Refund; values: Money, IdempotencyKey, TransactionStatus)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Notifications",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["NotificationRequest (root: notificationId; values: Channel, Template, DeliveryStatus)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Customer Identity",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["Customer (root: customerId; entities: CustomerProfile; values: Email, PhoneNumber, SavedAddress, PaymentMethodToken)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Courier Operations",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Order Management publishes OrderPlaced; Courier Operations consumes and acts independently. Order team accommodates Courier team's event schema needs."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Notifications",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Notifications is a conformist consumer; it adapts to whatever events Order publishes."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Location Tracking",
        "downstream": "Courier Operations",
        "relationship": "Open Host Service — Location Tracking exposes a published language (position events + query API) consumed by Courier Operations."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Payments",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier with ACL — Order Management calls Payment Service through an anti-corruption layer that translates order concepts into payment concepts (charge amount, idempotency key)."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Customer Identity",
        "downstream": "Order Management",
        "relationship": "Shared Kernel — both share customerId as an identity reference. Minimal shared surface, just the ID type."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Location Tracking",
        "downstream": "Notifications",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — GeofenceTriggered events consumed by Notifications for 'courier arriving' alerts."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Synchronous call from Order Service to Payment Service for charge authorization",
      "gains": "Guarantees payment is authorized before confirming order — strong consistency where it matters most (money). Simple failure handling: if payment fails, order fails.",
      "sacrifices": "Temporal coupling between Order and Payment. If Payment Service is down, order placement is blocked. Adds latency to order placement.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Async payment with eventual consistency (rejected: financial risk of confirming unpayable orders)", "Saga pattern with compensation (overkill for a single synchronous step; appropriate if the flow grows more complex)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Event choreography instead of central orchestrator",
      "gains": "Lower operational complexity for an 8-person team. No orchestrator service to maintain. Services are fully autonomous. Easier to reason about individual service behavior.",
      "sacrifices": "Harder to trace end-to-end order flow. Distributed logic can lead to 'lost' events. Debugging requires correlation IDs and distributed tracing.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Central saga orchestrator (rejected: adds operational burden and a single point of failure for a team at moderate operational maturity)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Dedicated time-series store for Location Tracking",
      "gains": "Purpose-built for 5K writes/sec of append-only GPS data. Efficient time-range queries. Built-in downsampling and retention policies.",
      "sacrifices": "Another database technology to operate. Team must learn time-series DB ops (backups, scaling, monitoring).",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Postgres with partitioned tables (viable up to ~3K writes/sec with tuning, but Location Tracking peaks at 5K — too close to the limit)", "Redis Streams (fast writes but no built-in retention or analytical queries)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Six services for an 8-engineer team",
      "gains": "Clean domain boundaries. Each service can be owned by 1-2 engineers. Deployment independence achieved.",
      "sacrifices": "Higher operational overhead than a monolith: 6 deployables, 6 databases, message broker, API gateway. Team must invest in CI/CD automation and observability.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Fewer services (e.g., merge Customer + Order) — rejected because customer identity lifecycle is genuinely different from order lifecycle", "More granular services — rejected because team size cannot support more than ~6 services effectively"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Notification channels",
      "evolution_path": "Notification Service uses a pluggable adapter pattern for channels. Adding a new channel (e.g., WhatsApp, in-app) requires only a new adapter — no changes to upstream services."
    },
    {
      "area": "Courier assignment algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "Assignment logic is encapsulated within Courier Service. Can evolve from simple nearest-courier to ML-based optimization without affecting other services."
    },
    {
      "area": "Payment gateway provider",
      "evolution_path": "Payment Service wraps gateway calls behind an ACL/adapter. Switching from Stripe to Adyen or adding a secondary provider is isolated to this service."
    },
    {
      "area": "Location Tracking throughput",
      "evolution_path": "If courier count grows beyond 500, Location Tracking can independently scale horizontally (shard by courier region) or switch to a streaming platform (Kafka) without affecting consumers — the event contract stays stable."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Order→Payment synchronous contract",
      "reason": "This coupling is intentionally rigid. Payment authorization MUST succeed before order confirmation. Changing this to async would require rethinking the entire order placement guarantee. This is rigidity by design."
    },
    {
      "area": "Domain event schemas",
      "reason": "Once consumers depend on event schemas (OrderPlaced, CourierAssigned, etc.), breaking changes require coordinated rollout. Use schema versioning from day one to manage this."
    },
    {
      "area": "Customer identity model (customerId)",
      "reason": "Shared across all services as a foreign reference. Changing the identity model (e.g., multi-tenant, anonymous orders) would be a cross-cutting change. Lock this down early."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Operational maturity gap — team has run a monolith for 3 years and now must operate 6 services, a message broker, an API gateway, and multiple databases",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Phased migration via strangler fig. Extract one service at a time. Invest heavily in CI/CD, centralized logging (ELK/Datadog), distributed tracing (Jaeger/OpenTelemetry), and alerting BEFORE extracting the first service. Budget 2-3 months for platform infrastructure."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Event loss or duplication in choreography-based architecture leading to inconsistent state (e.g., order placed but courier never assigned)",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Use a durable message broker (e.g., Kafka, RabbitMQ with persistence). Implement idempotent consumers. Add a reconciliation job that detects orders stuck in 'placed' without assignment after N minutes. Correlation IDs on all events for traceability."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Location Tracking write throughput becomes a bottleneck during growth beyond 500 couriers",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Current 5K writes/sec is manageable with a time-series DB. For 2x-5x growth, partition by geographic region. For 10x+, buffer writes through Kafka before persistence. Design the ingestion API to be stateless and horizontally scalable from day one."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Distributed transaction complexity for order placement (payment + order state + courier assignment)",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Keep the critical path narrow: Order Service does a synchronous call to Payment, then persists order and publishes event atomically (transactional outbox pattern). Courier assignment is async and non-blocking. Avoids multi-service distributed transactions entirely."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Team fragmentation — 8 engineers across 6 services means thin coverage per service, making on-call and knowledge sharing difficult",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Pair services for ownership: (1) Order + Payment, (2) Courier + Location Tracking, (3) Customer Account + Notification. Each pair owned by 2-3 engineers. Rotate ownership quarterly. Maintain shared coding standards and service templates."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Phase 1 (Months 1-2): Build observability and CI/CD platform — centralized logging, distributed tracing, per-service deployment pipelines, service template with health checks. Phase 2 (Months 2-4): Extract Location Tracking Service first — it has the most divergent NFRs (time-series writes), fewest inbound dependencies, and can be strangled behind a simple API. Stand up message broker. Phase 3 (Months 4-6): Extract Payment Service — strict consistency boundary, synchronous API, clear contract. Phase 4 (Months 6-9): Extract Courier Service and Notification Service in parallel (different teams). Phase 5 (Months 9-10): Extract Order Service (requires all downstream services to be stable). Phase 6 (Month 10-11): Extract Customer Account Service last (least urgency, simple CRUD). Decommission monolith.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "docs/adr/001-microservice-decomposition.md — Architecture Decision Record documenting this decomposition",
      "docs/adr/002-location-tracking-time-series-db.md — ADR for time-series DB choice",
      "docs/adr/003-event-choreography.md — ADR for choreography over orchestration",
      "docs/context-map.md — Visual context map of bounded contexts and relationships",
      "docs/event-catalog.md — Catalog of all domain events with schemas and ownership",
      "infra/service-template/ — Standardized service scaffold (health check, metrics, tracing, Dockerfile, CI config)",
      "infra/docker-compose.yml — Local development environment with all services, broker, and databases"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Transactional Outbox for reliable event publishing. Idempotency keys on all payment operations. Correlation IDs propagated through all events and API calls. Schema versioning for events from day one (e.g., CloudEvents envelope with type + specversion). Circuit breaker on the Order→Payment synchronous call. Health check endpoints on every service. Structured logging with service name, correlation ID, and trace ID.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Do NOT extract all services simultaneously — the team lacks operational maturity for a big-bang migration",
      "Do NOT share databases between services — this re-creates monolith coupling at the data layer",
      "Do NOT skip the observability investment — without centralized tracing and logging, debugging distributed failures is nearly impossible",
      "Do NOT use synchronous calls between services except where consistency absolutely requires it (only Order→Payment)",
      "Do NOT version events reactively — design schemas with forward compatibility from the start",
      "Do NOT let the API gateway accumulate business logic — it should only handle routing, auth, and rate limiting",
      "Avoid distributed transactions / two-phase commit — use the transactional outbox pattern instead"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 82,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Service boundary decomposition — these align cleanly to domain boundaries with minimal cross-cutting concerns",
      "Location Tracking as a separate service with time-series store — clear NFR divergence justifies isolation",
      "Payment as synchronous call with idempotency — well-established pattern for financial operations",
      "Phased strangler fig migration — proven approach for monolith decomposition with moderate-maturity teams"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Exact throughput ceiling for time-series DB choice — 5K writes/sec is within range of multiple solutions; would need benchmarking to confirm",
      "Team pairing for service ownership — depends on existing team skills and preferences not provided",
      "Migration timeline (10-11 months) — highly dependent on monolith code quality, test coverage, and data migration complexity"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The monolith uses a single relational database — if it already has multiple stores, extraction is easier",
      "The 5,000 writes/sec for location tracking is a sustained peak, not a burst — burst patterns would change the storage choice",
      "The team is willing to invest in operational infrastructure (CI/CD, observability) before extracting services",
      "There is no hard deadline forcing a faster migration — the phased approach assumes the monolith can coexist with new services"
    ]
  }
}

